Memory Forensics > [T1]: Analyzing KDBG Signatures

Volatility2's kdbgscan Plugin

The imageinfo plugin is not very good at scanning the subject dump and locating the KDBG signature because of the way it works. It scans the dump for all possible KDBG signatures (a KDBG signature is nothing but a hex string like 4b 44 42 47 40 03) and stops after hitting the first match, and will not scan the remaining content of the dump.

Sometimes, particularly large dump files, the dump may have content identical to the KDBG signatures (false positives). If the imageinfo plugin scan hits one of these false positive matches first, it will incorrectly report the target profile, ruining the whole analysis process.

The kdbgscan plugin exists to solve this problem by scanning the entire dump (it does not stop at the first hit) and extracting all possible KDBG signatures. The plugin output lists all identified KDBGs signatures offsets (i.e., memory addresses) and the suggested profile for each identified KDBG signature.


Here's an example scenario of when the kdbgscan plugin can be useful

  1. You run the imageinfo plugin to determine the image profile. Let's assume the suggested profiles were multiple builds of Windows 10 and one build of Windows 2016.
  2. You picked one of the above profiles and started your memory analysis by listing all processes available in the memory dump using the 'pslist' plugin (which will be explained later). However, the 'pslist' plugin does not show any process. In this case, you suspect that you are using the wrong profile.
  3. You run the 'kdbgscan' plugin to identify all possible KDBGs signatures in the dump and their corresponding offsets. For each identified KDBG signature, kdbgscan will list the number of discovered processes and modules. If discovered processes and modules are 0, then most probably, this is a false positive KDBG.
  4. You run the 'pslist' plugin again, but this time by specifying the correct profile and KDBG virtual offset identified in the previous step (e.g., --kdbg=0xf80001175cf0). Note that the '--KDBG' parameter is replaced by --KdCopyDataBlock in Windows 8 and subsequent releases.
  5. The 'pslist' will parse the dump correctly and list all discovered processes.

Here is how the process works:


zoom in

  1. Run the imageinfo plugin to determine suggested profiles. As you can see, all suggested profiles are for Windows 10 (different builds) except for one profile for Windows 2016. We can assume that, most probably, this is a Windows 10 system, although we are not sure yet which build.

zoom in

  1. Pick one of the suggested Windows 10 profiles and use it with the kdbgscan plugin. We used the first suggested profile from the imageinfo plugin output in this example. However, you can use any other Windows 10 profile.
  2. Note down the address/offset of 'KdCopyDataBlock' (or 'kdbg' in Windows releases before Windows 8). We will use this address later with 'PLIST' and other plugins to accurately and quickly parse the memory content.
  3. Note down the confirmed profile to use later with other plugins. The two fields 'Version64' and 'Build String' confirm that the accurate build number is 17763, so the correct profile will be 'Win10x64_17763', one of the suggested profiles by imageinfo.

    Note the number of discovered processes (126) next to the "PsActiveProcessHead". An indicator of the correct profile.

zoom in

Finally, run the 'pslist' plugin and use the suggested profile and the 'KdCopyDataBlock' address you get from kdbgscan. 


Notes:

  • Besides the 'PSLIST' plugin, many other Volatility plugins use the 'kdCopyDataBlock' to function.
  • Running the 'kdbgscan' plugin usually takes more time than 'imageinfo' because it scans the entire memory for KDBG signatures and does not stop after the first hit.
  • While you can run the 'kdbgscan' plugin without a profile, it will take a longer time to finish, and that's why we used one of the suggested profiles by 'imageinfo'. Doing this narrows down the scope of work of 'kdbgscan' and makes it finish faster.
